More PR spin. Sony desperately needs Blu-Ray to be relevant in order
to sell PS3's. From from a business perspective, I think they have
known that from the start. The problem isn't that this information is
false, because easy to validate, it's acurate data. The problem is it
doesn't matter.

What they aren't telling you is the very tough road ahead for Blu-Ray
and HD-DVD and any future format the tries to compete with DVD. Here's
why: consumers need a compelling reason to upgrade. The techno buffs
are going to run out and buy the latest and greatest technology first,
once they are made their investment (which accounts for about 1-5% of
the market, about where both HD-DVD and Blu-Ray are now in the grand
scheme of home movie media). Once you get past those guys it becomes
very difficult to penetrate the mass market.

Joe consumers doesn't care about Blu-Ray or HD-DVD because he has
figured out there is little incentive. He already has his 5.1 surround
sound, he already has menus, extra features and even 16x9 widescreen
picture, which at progressive scan, scaled to 1080i looks pretty damn
good. Joe consumer realizes that the only benefit this technology
offers him is "true" HD and after seeing the in store demo quickly
makes one of two decisions. 1. He doesn't have a HD Television so he
walks away without a second thought or 2. He rationalizes that the
nominal difference his eyes can see in the picture quality aren't
worth the $500 investment and the $10 per movie premium he will pay.
He probably also rationalizes that in addition to the $10 premium,
with Blu-Ray or HD-DVD he would have the added handicap of not being
able to play his movies in the upstairs bed room DVD player, his
notebook computer or his decked out SUV with in-car DVD system.

I think when you really consider all of this, it takes a very ignorant
person to assume Blu-Ray adoption will follow the same path as DVD.

If Blu-Ray has performed better than DVD in the similar time frame, I
would say it's because we have more technology buffs today. We're
still no where near mass market with these technology, Sony knows it,
everyone knows it. They are being careful....

