The PS3's sales in North America and (especially) Japan have fallen far
below expectations. The European launch looks great on paper, because
Sony had a ton of time to stockpile consoles in preparation for the
launch, a luxury not afforded to the Xbox 360 or Wii.

If Sony sells another 600K consoles in Europe next month, then the PS3
is off to an amazing start. If they sell 150K, it means Sony was able to
meet early adopter demand in one weekend instead of spreading it over
several months due to supply shortages, as with the 360 and Wii. Which
is still a good thing -- the quicker you sell to the hardcore crowd, the
quicker you sell games and make money -- but it's no indication that the
PS3 is a runaway success.

